--- body ---
## Context
Ticket 0182 asked whether the manuscript claim (A.1 tripod / A.5) — that
the three pre-2007 intellectual traditions were structurally separate —
survives a density-conditioned null once the labelling is kept clean of
community detection. Corrected dual run (N = 1000, seed 42, n_truncated = 0,
single primary statistic within_tradition_share; modularity is only its
affine companion, = share − K):

- **a_priori_anchors** — the non-circular test. Seed-sets fixed STRICTLY
  from the @tbl-traditions Key references (no community detection). Result:
  only 3 co-citation-core nodes match, ALL environmental economics;
  development and burden_sharing match zero. Induced subgraph 3 nodes /
  1 edge, one tradition → within_tradition_share = 1.0 trivially, null
  1.0 ± 0.0, z = NaN, p = 1. The test cannot be run as a three-way
  separation: the aid (desrosieres, michaelowa) and burden-sharing
  (negishi, stadelmann) anchor works are not among the 250 most co-cited
  pre-2007 references, and reference-node first-author metadata is sparse.
- **louvain_anchored** — comparison only, CIRCULAR. The Louvain communities
  the figure anchors (84 nodes / 369 edges) separate cleanly: share 0.889
  vs null 0.374 (z = 25.4), unweighted modularity 0.50 vs −0.01 (same z, it
  is share − K). But that partition is optimised on the very graph the null
  tests, so it corroborates the historical reading only weakly.

Verdict (0182, 2026-07-08T14:33Z): DEMOTE / non-circular test inconclusive.
The separation is NOT refuted — the fitted partition separates strongly —
but there is no independent, non-circular confirmation. A.5 states this
honestly as descriptive consistency, not as a passed density-conditioned
null.

